{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14932"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.76,0.07,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract infections are most commonly caused by uropathogenic \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E. These bacteria must first attach to the urinary tract epithelium to establish infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacterial structures is primarily responsible for attachment to urinary tract epithelial cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flagella","Fimbriae","Capsule","Cell wall peptidoglycan","Lipopolysaccharide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFimbriae\u003C/strong\u003E (also called pili) are hair-like protein structures that extend from the bacterial surface and contain adhesins that specifically bind to receptors on host cells. In uropathogenic \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E, type 1 and P fimbriae are particularly important for attachment to urinary tract epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlagella\u003C/strong\u003E are whip-like structures used for bacterial motility but do not primarily function in adhesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe bacterial \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsule\u003C/strong\u003E is a polysaccharide layer that provides protection against host immune responses and prevents desiccation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECell wall peptidoglycan\u003C/strong\u003E provides structural support and cell shape but is not involved in adhesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipopolysaccharide\u003C/strong\u003E is an endotoxin in the outer membrane of gram-negative bacteria but does not mediate attachment\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacterial adhesion via fimbriae is a critical first step that allows colonisation and subsequent infection of the urinary tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fimbriae (pili) are hair-like protein structures that allow bacteria to adhere to host cell surfaces.","Uropathogenic Escherichia coli uses type 1 and P fimbriae to attach to urinary tract epithelial cells.","Bacterial adhesion is a critical first step in establishing urinary tract infections."],"references":["Leonard JM, Toro DD. Defining the Microbiome Components (Bacteria, Viruses, Fungi) and Microbiome Geodiversity. Surg Infect (Larchmt). 2023 Apr;24(3):208-212. doi: 10.1089/sur.2023.014. PMID: 37010972; PMCID: PMC10061322.","M\u00fcller CM, Aberg A, Strasevi\u00e7iene J, Emody L, Uhlin BE, Balsalobre C. Type 1 fimbriae, a colonization factor of uropathogenic Escherichia coli, are controlled by the metabolic sensor CRP-cAMP. PLoS Pathog. 2009 Feb;5(2):e1000303. doi: 10.1371/journal.ppat.1000303. Epub 2009 Feb 20. PMID: 19229313; PMCID: PMC2636892.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T23:20:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T23:21:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null